  "id": "019cdcdc-fd00-7850-9bc2-aa2c85e6fc73",
  "content": " == \"key_section\");\n    }\n\n    #[test]\n    fn test_name_and_extensions() {\n        let chunker = ConfigChunker::new();\n        assert_eq!(chunker.name(), \"config\");\n        assert_eq!(chunker.supported_extensions(), &[\"toml\", \"yaml\", \"yml\", \"json\"]);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Step 2: Register module and run tests to verify they fail**\n\nAdd to `crates/corvia-kernel/src/lib.rs`:\n```rust\npub mod chunking_config_fmt;\n```\n\nRun: `cargo test -p corvia-kernel chunking_config_fmt -- --nocapture`\nExpected: FAIL\n\n**Step 3: Implement ConfigChunker**\n\nThree sub-strategies based on extension:\n- **TOML**: Split on `[section]` headers (regex: `^\\[`). Each section header + following key-value pairs = one chunk.\n- **YAML**: Split on top-level keys (lines that start at column 0 and end with `:`). Each top-level key + nested content = one chunk.\n- **JSON**: Parse with serde_json, split on top-level object keys. If the file is a top-level array or primitive, return as single chunk.\n\nAll three use `chunk_type = \"section\"`.\n\nThe `overlap_context()` override prepends the parent key path for nested sections.\n\n**Step 4: Run tests to verify they pass**\n\nRun: `cargo test -p corvia-kernel chunking_config_fmt -- --nocapture`\nExpected: All tests PASS\n\n**Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add crates/corvia-kernel/src/chunking_config_fmt.rs crates/corvia-kernel/src/lib.rs\ngit commit -m \"feat(m3.3): ConfigChunker — TOML/YAML/JSON section splitting (D68)\"\n```\n\n---\n",
